3

  3. Pre-registration
Want to know more about...
The purpose of pre-registering a study?
Take a look at this short introductory video on pre-registration: Introduction to Pre-registration
Read this newspaper article titled: Trust in science would be improved by study pre-registration{target="_blank"}
Read about: Seven Selfish Reasons for Pre-registration{target="_blank"}
And this brief outline of why pre-registration is ‚ÄúA Plan, Not a Prison{target="_blank"}‚Äù
How to pre-register?
Pre-registration and Registered Reports: A primer from UKRN Additional resources on Pre-registration are also available through the Center for Open Science{target="_blank"}
What journals give a digital badge for pre-registration? See OSF-Badges{target="_blank"} for this list
How to navigate OSF? This short video on Getting started with OSF: Sign up, navigate OSF, register your study{target="_blank"}
Supplemental Reading
The benefits of registered reports and pre-registration, including for students
Pownall, M. (2020, February 24). Pre-Registration in the Undergraduate Dissertation: A Critical Discussion. https://doi.org/10.31234/osf.io/egbcv{target="_blank"}
Hobson, H. (2019). Registered reports are an ally to early career researchers. Nature Human Behaviour, 3, 1010. https://doi.org/10.1038/s41562-019-0701-8{target="_blank"}
Nosek, B.A., Beck, E.D., Campbell, L., Flake, J.K., Hardwicke, T.E., Mellor, D.T., van 't Veer, A.E., & Vazire, S. (2019). pre-registration Is Hard, And Worthwhile. Trends in Cognitive Sciences, 23(10), 815-818. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.tics.2019.07.009{target="_blank"}
On the uses, pitfalls, and potential successors to the Pre-registration model
Yamada, Y. (2018). How to Crack Pre-registration: Toward Transparent and Open Science. Frontiers in Psychology, 9, 1831. https://doi.org/10.3389/fpsyg.2018.01831{target="_blank"}
On the role of pre-registration in improving the integrity of research, even when data is pre-existing
Nosek, B. A., Ebersole, C. R., DeHaven, A. C., & Mellor, D. T. (2018). The Pre-registration revolution. Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America, 115(11), 2600‚Äì2606. https://doi.org/10.1073/pnas.1708274114{target="_blank"}
On the benefits and appropriateness of pre-registration in qualitative studies
Haven, T.L., & Van Grootel, L. (2019). pre-registering qualitative research. Policies and Quality Assurance, 26(3), 229-244. https://doi.org/10.1080/08989621.2019.1580147{target="_blank"}

4

  4. Data Management

Want to know more about...
Open data and data repositories?
Take a look at this handy guide on selecting a data repository: OpenAIRE Guide for Researchers: How to Select a Data Repository{target="_blank"}
You can read about some concerns and challenges of using open data repositories here Open data repositories: current risks and opportunities{target="_blank"}
One researcher‚Äôs experience of sharing data? Don‚Äôt worry, its not as scary as the name of this blogpost suggests: Open Science is really scary y‚Äôall{target="_blank"}
On the challenges of open data sharing
This article discusses some perceived barriers to open data sharing in psychology (but is relevant across disciplines) Houtkoop, B. L., Chambers, C., Macleod, M., Bishop, D. V., Nichols, T. E., & Wagenmakers, E. J. (2018). Data sharing in psychology: A survey on barriers and preconditions. Advances in methods and practices in psychological science, 1(1), 70-85. https://doi.org/10.1177/2515245917751886{target="_blank"}
Data management and archiving for qualitative data?
This paper{target="_blank"} outlines how software like NVivo can be used to manage your qualitative data
You can also check out the Irish Qualitative Data Archive{target="_blank"}, which provides lots of useful information and resources
Or take a look at the Qualitative Data Repository{target="_blank"}
This paper outlines some challenges with making some qualitative data open: Chauvette et al. (2019). Open data in qualitative research. International Journal of Qualitative Methods, 18. https://doi.org/10.1177/1609406918823863{target="_blank"}
This paper presents an examination of repository guidelines for sharing qualitative data Antes et al. (2018). Examining data repository guidelines for qualitative data sharing. Journal of Empirical Research on Human Research Ethics, 13(1), 61-73. https://doi.org/10.1177/1556264617744121{target="_blank"}
Use of spreadsheets for data management
This is a handy article outlining practical recommendations for organizing spreadsheet data. Broman, K. & Woo, K (2018). Data organization in spreadsheets. The American Statistician, 72(1), 2-10. https://doi.org/10.1080/00031305.2017.1375989{target="_blank"}
Discipline-specific Research Data Management?
Take a look at the Science Europe Guidance Document: Presenting a Framework for Discipline-specific Research Data Management{target="_blank"}. This looks like a long document but there is an over-all section, followed by discipline-specific sections that will be of more, or less, relevance to you.
The use of FAIR Principles?
This article clarifies what FAIRness is, and what it is not Mons et al.(2017) ‚ÄòCloudy, Increasingly FAIR; Revisiting the FAIR Data Guiding Principles for the European Open Science Cloud‚Äô. Information Services and Use, 49 ‚Äì 56. https://doi.org/10.3233/ISU-170824{target="_blank"}
This article discusses the FAIR principles and presents useful examples of their use: Wilkinson et al. The FAIR Guiding Principles for scientific data management and stewardship. Sci Data 3, 160018 (2016). https://doi.org/10.1038/sdata.2016.18{target="_blank"}
How research data management, FAIR and Open are related to each other?
This article clarifies presents the overlaps and distinctions between these three concepts Higman R, Bangert D and Jones S, ‚ÄúThree camps, one destination: the intersections of research data management, FAIR and Open‚Äù, Insights, 2019, 32: 18, 1‚Äì9; DOI: http://doi.org/10.1629/uksg.468
Resources for data management in University College Cork
The UCC Research Data Service{target="_blank"} provides information, including videos and resources.

5

  5. Reproducible Research Practices

Want to know more about...
The reproducibility crisis?
Check out this comic strip about the reproducibility crisis; it focuses on psychology but is relevant across disciplines: Repeat After Me: A Cartoon about Reproducibility in Psychology{target="_blank"}
This blog gives a nice overview, and includes reference to the power posing study we mentioned earlier: Failure is Moving Science Forward: The replication crisis is a sign that science is working{target="_blank"}
Take a look at this short video about the ‚Äòreproducibility crisis‚Äô. The focus in the video is on science but even if you are not studying science, it presents a useful overview and interesting examples of existing reproducibility issues that are relevant across research disciplines.
{width="313"}
Reproducibility in qualitative research and the humanities
This paper gives an overview and practical guidelines for reproducibility in the humanities: Peels, R., Bouter, L. (2018). The possibility and desirability of replication in the humanities. Palgrave Commun 4, 95. https://doi.org/10.1057/s41599-018-0149-x{target="_blank"}
The paper outlines 12 transparency criteria for qualitative work that can help boost transparency and reproducibility: Aguinis, H. & Solarino, A.M. (2019). Transparency and replicability in qualitative research: The case of interviews with elite informants. Strategic Management Journal, 40(8), 1291-1315. https://doi.org/10.1002/smj.3015{target="_blank"}
How to make your research more transparent and/or reproducible?
Robert Peng‚Äôs 3-part Video Checklist for Reproducible Research can help. There are three parts, about 10 minutes each: 1{target="_blank"}, 2{target="_blank"}, and 3{target="_blank"}
The relationship between registered reports and reproducibility? We introduced registered reports in Module 2 and this video draws a link between registered reports and reproducibility Registered Reports as a tool for improving research transparency and reproducibility{target="_blank"}
Strategies for minimising normal human biases in research
This paper details one researchers experiences and gives tips on how we can ‚Äòfight our own worst instincts‚Äô in research: Nuzzo, R. (2015). Fooling ourselves. Nature, 526(7572), 182-185. https://www.nature.com/news/how-scientists-fool-themselves-and-how-they-can-stop-1.18517{target="_blank"}
Software for reproducibility Take a look at this ‚Äòtoolkit‚Äô, which focuses mainly on computational reproducibility: Perkel, J.M. (2018). A toolkit for data transparency takes shape. Nature, 560(7719), 513-515. https://doi.org/10.1038/d41586-018-05990-5{target="_blank"}
Large-scale reproducibility evaluations
The links below give an overview of some large-scale projects and let you take a look at some of the reproducibility studies that have been conducted Reproducibility Project: Psychology{target="_blank"} Many Labs Replication Project{target="_blank"} Replicability Index{target="_blank"}
The Power Posing example we introduced earlier
This article gives an overview of the power posing research, including criticisms and support of the findings Power Posing is Back: Amy Cuddy Successfully Refutes Criticism{target="_blank"}
